Introduction

Our objective for this project is to investigate the various relationships between variables in the Pima Indians Diabetes Database by performing supervised and unsupervised learning classifications. The dataset we are using is called PimaIndiansDiabetes, which has 768 observations on 9 variables that display various medical statistics for women of Pima Indian heritage. The variables include number of times pregnant, plasma glucose concentration, blood pressure, tricep skin thickness, insulin concentration, BMI, diabetes pedigree function, age, and if the patient has diabetes or not. We converted the categorical variable of does a patient have diabetes or not from yes and no to binary 1 or 0, respectively. For this variable, 268 of the patients in the dataset have diabetes (1), and 500 do not have diabetes (0). We found our dataset by searching for machine learning R packages within the Machine Learning Mastery website (https://machinelearningmastery.com/machine-learning-datasets-in-r/).

Statistic Function

The function aim to summary the evaluation parameter of models. Including: accuracy, sensitivity, specificity and AUC

class_diag <- function(score, truth, positive, cutoff=.5){
  
  pred <- factor(score>cutoff,levels=c("TRUE","FALSE"))
  truth <- factor(truth==positive, levels=c("TRUE","FALSE"))
  
  tab<-table(truth, pred)
  acc=sum(diag(tab))/sum(tab)
  sens=tab[1,1]/rowSums(tab)[1]
  spec=tab[2,2]/rowSums(tab)[2]
  ppv=tab[1,1]/colSums(tab)[1]
  
  #CALCULATE EXACT AUC
  truth<-as.numeric(truth=="TRUE")
  ord<-order(score, decreasing=TRUE)
  score <- score[ord]; truth <- truth[ord]
  TPR=cumsum(truth)/max(1,sum(truth))
  FPR=cumsum(!truth)/max(1,sum(!truth))
  dup<-c(score[-1]>=score[-length(score)], FALSE)
  TPR<-c(0,TPR[!dup],1); FPR<-c(0,FPR[!dup],1)
  n <- length(TPR)
  auc<- sum( ((TPR[-1]+TPR[-n])/2) * (FPR[-1]-FPR[-n]) )
  round(data.frame(acc,sens,spec,auc, row.names = "Metrics"),4)
}

Split train and test data function

train_set<-function(data1, proportion,model){
  idx_train <- sample(1:nrow(data1), floor(proportion * nrow(data1)))
  PID_train <- data1[idx_train,]
  PID_test <- data1[-idx_train,]
  return(model(PID_train,PID_test))
}

lr_prima_model2 <- function(PID_training,PID_testing){

dt_model <- function(PID_train,PID_test){
  PID_dt_train <- rpart(diabetes_new ~ .,
                data = PID_train, 
                control = rpart.control(cp = 0.034))
  predicted <- predict(PID_dt_train, PID_test)
  M<-class_diag(predicted[,2],truth=PID_test$diabetes_new, positive=1)
  return(M)
}

Regression/Numeric Prediction

Create a rmse_model function to return the RMSE for a model with the input of the real observation(outcome) and their predicted values (predict_outcome) from a model, RMSE reflects the difference between them.

rmse_model <- function(outcome, predict_outcome) {
  rmse <- sqrt(mean((outcome - predict_outcome)^2))
  return(rmse)
}

We are interested in learning the relationship between glucose concentration with blood pressure, triceps, insulin, body mass, etc. and we wanted to know what variable have a bigger weight in affecting the glucose level.

We fit a multiple linear regression with glucose concentration as the dependent variable and all other independent variables except for diabetes_new (reflects whether a Pima Indian has diabetes or not). We wanted to study whether this model works better with or without the diabetes_new.

glucose_lm <- lm(glucose ~. -diabetes_new, data = PID)
print(glucose_lm)

##     6.31624      0.64526
glucose_predict <- glucose_lm$fitted.values
rmse_model(glucose_predict, PID$glucose)
## [1] 28.03478

The RMSE for this model (without diabetes_new) is 28.035.and pedigree (likelihood of diabetes based on family history) has the biggest coefficient value.

Next, we run a similar model but this time, we include diabetes_new as our independent variable to see if the model works better.

glucose_lm2 <- lm(glucose ~.,data = PID)
print(glucose_lm2)

The RMSE for this model is 25.874, which is smaller than the previous model. Since this model works better and diabetes_new is a good variable to predict glucose concentration, we should include it in the model. Some coefficients change the sign and diabetes_new becomes the variable with the highest weight on changes for glucose predictions.

How does the results from k-fold cross-validation between the two methods compare? Which method seems to perform best?

Answer: Focusing on the most optimal model (mtry=2) of the cv_lm_rf model, we found that the RMSE of a random forest with k-fold cross-validation method to be 26.211, much smaller than the RMSE we draw out of the random forest model itself. Besides the smaller RMSE, the random forest model also has slightly higher Rsquared (0.334, compared to 0.324). However, in my opinion, this difference is not significant so I believe both methods deliver equal performance.

how much of the total variance in your dataset is accounted for by the PCs you decide to retain. Do the PCs capture most of the variance in the data? Answer: Based on the PCA rotation, triceps thickness, insulin concentration, and BMI appear to contribute the most to PC1. However, pregnancy and age appear to contribute the most to PC2. We calculated the proportion of variance accounted for by each PC and determined that about 47.8% of the variance in our data can be attributed to the first two principle components. The PCs only capture half of the variance in our entire dataset.
